=Description=

'''1. Regina Gelfo:'''

"The Gift Circle, as founded by Alpha Lo and spread by Charles Eisenstein, is a group facilitation format that holds great possibility as a way to match resources with needs, create community and inspire gratitude and generosity. The goals of a Gift Circle are simply to provide a warm, free, and welcoming space for community to gather and share Gifts and Needs, most often while literally sitting in a circle.  Perhaps most importantly, I believe that variations of the Gift Circle format also hold the potential to cultivate healthy interdependence in communities, providing a sense of psycho-spiritual belonging and connection to ameliorate the vast sense of alienation and scarcity experienced by so many."
(http://www.shareable.net/blog/how-to-integrate-gift-circles-into-any-community)


'''2. Charles Eistenstein:'''

"Given the cirôÙcuôÙlar naôÙture of gift flow, I was exôÙcited to learn that one of the most promisôÙing soôÙcial inôÙvenôÙtions that I've come across for buildôÙing comôÙmuôÙnity is called the Gift CirôÙcle. DeôÙvelôÙoped by Alpha Lo, co-auôÙthor of The Open ColôÙlabôÙoôÙraôÙtion EnôÙcyôÙcloôÙpeôÙdia, and his friends in Marin County, CalôÙiôÙforôÙnia, it exôÙemôÙpliôÙfies the dyôÙnamôÙics of gift sysôÙtems and ilôÙluôÙmiôÙnates the broad ramôÙiôÙfiôÙcaôÙtions that gift economies porôÙtend for our econôÙomy, psyôÙcholôÙogy, and civôÙiôÙlizaôÙtion.

The ideal numôÙber of parôÙticôÙiôÙpants in a gift cirôÙcle is 10-20. EveryôÙone sits in a cirôÙcle, and takes turns sayôÙing one or two needs they have. In the last cirôÙcle I faôÙcilôÙiôÙtated, some of the needs shared were: "a ride to the airôÙport next week," "someôÙone to help reôÙmove a fence," "used lumôÙber to build a garôÙden," "a ladôÙder to clean my gutôÙter," "a bike," and "ofôÙfice furôÙniôÙture for a comôÙmuôÙnity cenôÙter." As each perôÙson shares, othôÙers in the cirôÙcle can break in to offer to meet the stated need, or with sugôÙgesôÙtions of how to meet it.

When everyôÙone has had their turn, we go around the cirôÙcle again, each perôÙson statôÙing someôÙthing he or she would like to give. Some exôÙamôÙples last week were "Graphic deôÙsign skills," "the use of my power tools," "conôÙtacts in local govôÙernôÙment to get things done," and "a bike," but it could be anyôÙthing: time, skills, maôÙteôÙrôÙial things; the gift of someôÙthing outôÙright, or the gift of the use of someôÙthing (borôÙrowôÙing). Again, as each perôÙson shares, anyôÙone can speak up and say, "I'd like that," or "I know someôÙone who could use one of those.

DurôÙing both these rounds, it is useôÙful to have someôÙone write everyôÙthing down and send the notes out the next day to everyôÙone via email, or on a web page, blog, etc. OthôÙerôÙwise it is quite easy to forôÙget who needs and ofôÙfers what. Also, I sugôÙgest writôÙing down, on the spot, the name and phone numôÙber of someôÙone who wants to give or reôÙceive someôÙthing to/from you. It is esôÙsenôÙtial to folôÙlow up, or the gift cirôÙcle will end up feedôÙing cynôÙiôÙcism rather than comôÙmuôÙnity.

FiôÙnally, the cirôÙcle can do a third round in which peoôÙple exôÙpress gratôÙiôÙtude for the things they reôÙceived since the last meetôÙing. This round is exôÙtremely imôÙporôÙtant beôÙcause in comôÙmuôÙnity, the witôÙnessôÙing of othôÙers' genôÙerosôÙity inôÙspires genôÙerosôÙity in those who witôÙness it. It conôÙfirms that this group is givôÙing to each other, that gifts are recôÙogôÙnized, and that my own gifts will be recôÙogôÙnized, apôÙpreôÙciôÙated, and recôÙiôÙpôÙroôÙcated as well.

It is just that simôÙple: needs, gifts, and gratôÙiôÙtude. But the efôÙfects can be proôÙfound.

First, gift cirôÙcles (and any gift econôÙomy, in fact) can reôÙduce our deôÙpenôÙdence on the traôÙdiôÙtional marôÙket. If peoôÙple give us things we need, then we needn't buy them. I won't need to take a taxi to the airôÙport toôÙmorôÙrow, and Rachel won't have to buy lumôÙber for her garôÙden. The less we use money, the less time we need to spend earnôÙing it, and the more time we have to conôÙtribute to the gift econôÙomy, and then reôÙceive from it. It is a virôÙtuôÙous cirôÙcle.

SecôÙondly, a gift cirôÙcle reôÙduces our proôÙducôÙtion of waste. It is ridicuôÙlous to pump oil, mine metal, manôÙuôÙfacôÙture a table and ship it across the ocean when half the peoôÙple in town have old taôÙbles in their baseôÙments. It is ridicuôÙlous as well for each houseôÙhold on my block to own a lawnôÙmower, which they use two hours a month, a leaf blower they use twice a year, power tools they use for an ocôÙcaôÙsional proôÙject, and so on. If we shared these things, we would sufôÙfer no loss of qualôÙity of life. Our maôÙteôÙrôÙial lives would be just as rich, yet would reôÙquire less money and less waste.

